subject: libcr51sign: import from gBMC
commitMessage:
libcr51sign: import from gBMC

Validate the cr51 descriptor of the BIOS image. It can also
parse the BIOS version and write it to a file.

Signed-off-by: Nan Zhou <nanzhoumails@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I098be66b228da6f3514d3f13166a1bb4e1e718fb

Change has been successfully merged by Nan Zhou
Why do we want to comment this out?
yeah, the formatting we have internally does not match what we need in OpenBMC.
You can drop the array brackets and put each source on it's own line. All varargs are implied to be sources after the library name.
nit: inconsistent formatting with other endings being lisp style.
This is actually not needed anymore.
You should make the library the first positional argument, specifying `libraries:` is deprecated.
This should include the openssl dependency as it would be required if this was built statically.
Done. Referenced libcr51sign_lib directly which has openssl in its dependencies.
The implicit specification doesn't work if you include openssl headers from the public headers of libcr51sign. You still need to add the dependency here.
That's more subtle than I thought. Added to "requires" should solve the problem, right?
Yeah, I meant requires not dependencies.
Put this on a new line.
nit: do we want to use meson version of > 0.57.0 and c++20?
Should be `libcrypto` since you don't use the libssl part of openssl.
Needs to be a `c` project instead of `cpp` to build standalone
